lity - some systems don't support x16 organization properly. Let me think about whether Lenovo 81XJ supports it.\n\nLooking at the existing RAM:\n- RMSA3270ME86H9F-2666 - this appears to be a SO-DIMM DDR4-2666\n- Micron 4ATF51264HZ-3G2J1 - Micron DDR4-3200 SO-DIMM, 4GB, 1Rx16\n\nLet me decode that Micron part number to confirm - 4ATF indicates DDR4, the 512 and 64 refer to the density and bit width, HZ denotes SO-DIMM form factor, and 3G2J1 specifies the 3200 speed. So this is indeed a 4GB DDR4 SO-DIMM, and given the part number structure, it's likely a 1Rx16 configuration.\n\nSince the system already has a DDR4-3200 stick installed, it definitely supports DDR4-3200 speeds. The 8GB 1Rx16 module matches the SO-DIMM form factor and DDR4 type, but the 1Rx16 organization is unusual for an 8GB stick - most 8GB SO-DIMMs use 1Rx8 instead. This could potentially cause compatibility issues depending on how strict the system is about chip organization.\n\nHowever, the existing 4GB Micron stick might also be 1Rx16, and since it's working fine, the Lenovo 81XJ likely supports this configuration. So overall, the module should be compatible - it'll fit the form factor, match the DDR type, run at 3200MHz (or possibly downclock to 2667MHz), and the 1Rx16 organization shouldn't be a dealbreaker.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":362,"cache_read_input_tokens":36338,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":362},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYgjzma6mGsYhr1xk3cFN","type":"assistant","uuid":"af9734ca-5c7c-4d67-8961-f61aa69403d2","timestamp":"2026-03-03T20:01:44.432Z"}
